lege]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Edmund's School, Canterbury]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Canterbury]]\n[[Category:UNICEF Goodwill Ambassadors]]\n[[Category:Nichiren Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the British American Drama Academy]]\n[[Category:People with dyslexia]]\n", "name_user": "Luciap2005", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orlando_Bloom"}
{"title_page": "Abdellah Guennoun", "text_new": "[[File:Habib Burguiba, Abdallah Guennun y Allal El Fasi presidiendo un banquete en la ciudad de T\u00e1nger en abril de 1957.jpg|thumb|261px|Guennoun (standing) during a banquet in [[Tangier]], April 1957, next to [[Habib Bourguiba]] (with [[bow tie]]) and [[Allal al-Fassi]] (with [[fez]])]]\n{{Moroccan literature}}\n'''Abdellah Guennoun''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u06ad\u0646\u0648\u0646}} \u02bbAbd All\u0101h Gann\u016bn, Born 16 September 1908 in [[Fes]] \u2013 died 9 July 1989 in [[Tangier]]) was a famous and influential Moroccan writer, historian, essayist, poet, academic, administrator, journalist, and [[Faq\u012bh|''faq\u012bh'']].<ref>Literatura Marroqui [http://www.literaturamarroqui.edu.es/autores/GHENNUN,%20Abdallah%20(1908-1989).pdf] (retrieved Feb. 13, 2009)</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hespress.com/%D9%82%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%A1%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%90%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8/160281.html|title=\"\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a\" \u0644\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u0641\u064a \u0637\u0628\u0639\u0629 \u062c\u062f\u064a\u062f\u0629|website=Hespress|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> He was one of the leaders of the ''[[Nahda]]'' movement in Morocco, and served as the general secretary of the [[League of Moroccan Religious Scholars]] ({{Lang|ar|\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0637\u0629 \u0639\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628}}).<ref>[http://www.hespress.com/?browser=view&EgyxpID=18679 '''\u0647\u064a\u0633\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0633:''' \u0630\u0627\u0643\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u062a\u0624\u0633\u0633 \u0644\u0630\u0627\u0643\u0631\u0629 \u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u062d\u0642\u064a\u0642\u064a\u0629] \u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0635\u0648\u0644: 14 [[\u0641\u0628\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0631]] 2010]] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216155754/http://www.hespress.com/?browser=view&EgyxpID=18679|date=16 \u0641\u0628\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0631 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hespress.com/writers/383257.html|title=\u0639\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628.. \u0645\u0646 \u0631\u0627\u0628\u0637\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0621 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0637\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f\u064a\u0629|website=Hespress|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nHe is known for writing ''[[Al-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b|an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b]]'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a}}, ''Moroccan Intellect in Arabic Literature''),<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Simour|first=Lhoussain|url=https://books.google.co.ma/books?id=FABODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=guennoun+literature&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiG_6Xdo8DoAhUj2uAKHUKPDZ0Q6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=guennoun%20literature&f=false|title=Larbi Batma, Nass el-Ghiwane and Postcolonial Music in Morocco|date=2016-10-21|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-2581-2|language=en}}</ref> a three-volume anthology of [[Moroccan literature]] in [[Arabic]] that was banned by the [[French Protectorate in Morocco|French Protectorate]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.habous.gov.ma/daouat-alhaq/item/1234|title=\u062f\u0639\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0642 - [\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628] \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a (\u0644\u0640 \u0639.\u0644.\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646)|website=www.habous.gov.ma|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.maghress.com/almassae/211388|title=\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0644\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646.. \u0645\u0648\u0633\u0648\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0641\u064a \u062e\u0635\u0648\u0635\u064a\u062a\u0647 \u0648\u062a\u0639\u062f\u062f\u0647|website=\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0633|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \n\nGuennoun also served as a member of a number of linguistic, educational, and Islamic academies and organizations in places such as [[Rabat]], [[Cairo]], [[Damascus]], [[Baghdad]], and [[Amman]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://uemnet.free.fr/guide/kaf/kaf07.htm|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0640\u0648\u0646|website=uemnet.free.fr|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nAbdallah Guennoun was born in Fes in 1908 to a family of noble [[Idrisid dynasty|Idrissid]] lineage long associated with knowledge.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> His family moved from Fes to Tangier in 1914.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nHe had a traditional Islamic education, memorizing the [[Quran]] and some [[Hadith]].<ref name=\":4\" /> With access to international books in Tangier, he also taught himself [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[French language|French]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nGuennoun began his writing career early; he published in the newspaper [[Idhar al-Haqq|''Idhar al-Haqq'']] ({{Lang|ar|\u0625\u0638\u0647\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0642}}) in 1927 when he was 20 years old.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EGtlrenmK0A|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646 1 - \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628|date=Aug 24, 2016|work=\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0632\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0648\u062b\u0627\u0626\u0642\u064a\u0629|access-date=|url-status=live|language=Arabic}}</ref> He also wrote for publications such as the Egyptian literary magazine ''[[Arrissalah]].<ref name=\":4\" />''\n\nHe became active and influential in the flourishing intellectual and cultural scene in [[T\u00e9touan|Tetuan]], and he published many of his works there.<ref name=\":2\" /> As part of this intellectual circle in Tetuan, he was involved in the first nationalist publication in Morocco, ''[[As-Salaam (publication)|as-Salaam]]'', which published its first issue October 1933.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.habous.gov.ma/daouat-alhaq/item/5281|title=\u062f\u0639\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0642 - \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0623\u0648\u0644 \u0635\u062d\u064a\u0641\u0629 \u0648\u0637\u0646\u064a\u0629 \u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|website=www.habous.gov.ma|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAbdallah Guennoun was well-connected, associated with [[Said Hajji]] in the [[French Protectorate in Morocco|French area]], [[Mohammed Daoud]] in the [[Spanish protectorate in Morocco|Spanish area]], and [[Shakib Arslan]] in the ''[[Mashriq]]''.<ref name=\":2\" /> Guennoun became involved with the [[Moroccan Action Committee]] in 1934.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\nHe opened the first of the [[Moroccan free schools]] in Tangier, the Free Abdallah Guennoun School ({{Lang|ar|\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u0629 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0629}}), and worked as a teacher in 1936.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nHe was the editor in-chief of a monthly Islamic publication called [[Lisaan ad-Din (publication)|''Lisaan ad-Din'']] ({{Lang|ar|\u0644\u0633\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646}}) in the 1940s and published a number of articles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> He also served as the general secretary of [[Al-Mithaq (newspaper)|''al-Mithaq'']], a journal put out by the faculty of [[University of al-Qarawiyyin|al-Qarawiyyin University]].<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.habous.gov.ma/daouat-alhaq/item/5427|title=\u062f\u0639\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0642 - \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u0648\u0623\u062b\u0631\u0647 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062b\u0642\u0627\u0641\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 -2-|website=www.habous.gov.ma|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nHe refused the support [[Mohammed Ben Aarafa]], the [[puppet monarch]] chosen by France to replace [[Mohammed V of Morocco|Muhammad V]], whom France had exiled.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nGuennoun was, among other members of the [[Mococcan Nationalist Movement]] ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0637\u0646\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629}}) including [[Allal al-Fassi]], [[Abdelkhalek Torres]], [[Abdallah Ibrahim]], a member of a generation of Moroccan intellectuals brought together the political and the cultural, and who criticized the reform movement in the country, arguing that there can be \"no reform without independence.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n=== ''an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b'' ===\nIn 1938, he published ''[[Al-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b|an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b]]'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a}}, ''Moroccan Intellect in Arabic Literature''), his three-volume anthology of [[Moroccan literature]].<ref name=\":0\" /> This anthology indexed and contextualized major Moroccan works of literature written in [[Arabic]], and led to the development of a Moroccan literary canon.<ref name=\":3\" /> Affirming both Morocco's contributions to [[Arabic literature]] and the long tradition of Arabic literature in Morocco, ''an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b'' was seen as a nationalist reaction to colonialism.<ref name=\":3\" /> It was banned by the authorities of the [[French Protectorate in Morocco|French Protectorate]], and could not be brought into the area under French colonial control, nor could it be sold, displayed, or distributed there.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Spain, however, was receptive of the work; ''an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b'' was translated into Spanish and Abdallah Guennoun was granted an honorary doctorate from a university in Madrid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.belpresse.com/featured/105958.html|title=\u0627\u0644\u0630\u0643\u0631\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0626\u0648\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0645\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062f \u0635\u0627\u062d\u0628 '\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a'|date=2019-09-20|website=Belpresse {{!}} \u0628\u0644\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0633|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\nHe held a number of different positions. In 1937, he was made director of the [[Khalifi Institute]] ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u0647\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u0641\u064a}}),<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://uemnet.free.fr/guide/kaf/kaf07.htm|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0640\u0648\u0646|website=uemnet.free.fr|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://marayana.com/laune/2019/09/17/2457/|title=\u0641\u064a \u0630\u0643\u0631\u0649 \u0645\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062f\u0647: \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646\u2026 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0630\u064a \u0623\u0639\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0639\u062a\u0628\u0627\u0631 \u0644\u0644\u0641\u0643\u0631 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a|last=\u0627\u0644\u0647\u0627\u0646\u064a|first=\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0645|date=2019-09-17|website=Marayana - \u0645\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0627\u0646\u0627|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> then professor at the [[High Institute of Religion]] ({{Lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u0647\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u064a}}) and the [[College of Theology in Tetuan]] ({{Lang|ar|\u0643\u0644\u064a\u0629 \u0623\u0635\u0648\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u062a\u0637\u0648\u0627\u0646}}).<ref name=\":8\" /> He held the office of Minister of Justice in the Khalifi government from 1954 to 1956.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nHe became a member of the [[Arab Academy of Damascus]] in 1956, the [[Academy of the Arabic Language in Cairo]] in 1961, the [[League of Moroccan Religious Scholars]], the [[al-Quds Scientific Commission]] ({{Lang|ar|\u0647\u064a\u0626\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0629}}) in 1973, the [[Muslim World League]] in Mecca as a founding member in 1974, the [[Jordan Academy of Arabic]] in 1978, the [[Iraqi Academy of Sciences]] in 1979, and the [[Academy of the Kingdom of Morocco]] in 1980.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn 1981, he founded ''[[al-Ihyaa']]'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0625\u062d\u064a\u0627\u0621}} ''The Revival''), a journal published by the Association of Moroccan Academics focusing on Islamic theological sciences and thought from an open, critical perspective.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arrabita.ma/blog/%d9%86%d8%a8%d8%b0%d8%a9-%d8%aa%d8%b9%d8%b1%d9%8a%d9%81%d9%8a%d8%a9-%d8%b9%d9%86-%d9%85%d8%ac%d9%84%d8%a9-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%a5%d8%ad%d9%8a%d8%a7%d8%a1/|title=\u0646\u0628\u0630\u0629 \u062a\u0639\u0631\u064a\u0641\u064a\u0629 \u0639\u0646 \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u062d\u064a\u0627\u0621|date=2019-06-19|website=\u0628\u0648\u0627\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0637\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0621|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nAbdallah Guennoun passed away July 9, 1989 in Tangier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Notable works ==\nAbdallah Guennoun's works include poetry, literary fiction, and history. Some of his most notable works include:\n\n* ''[[Al-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b|an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b]]'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a}}, ''Moroccan Intellect in Arabic Literature''), 1st ed. [[al-Matba'a al-Mehdia]]. 1938; 2nd ed. [[Dar al-Kitab al-Lubnani]]. 1961; 1st ed. [[Dar al-Kutub al-Ilmiyah]]. 2014.\n* ''Umar\u0101\u02bcun\u0101 al-Shu\u02bbar\u0101\u02bc'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0623\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0624\u0646\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0621}} ''Our Poet Princes''). 1941.\n* ''al-Qudwat ul-Samiya lil-Nashi'at il-Islamiya'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0644\u0646\u0627\u0634\u0626\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629}}). 1945\n* ''Wahat al-Fikr'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0648\u0627\u062d\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0643\u0631}} ''The Oasis of Thought'')''.'' 1948.\n* ''D\u012bw\u0101n Malik Gharna\u1e6dah Yusuf al-Thalith'' ({{Lang|ar|\u062f\u064a\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0627\u0644\u0643 \u063a\u0631\u0646\u0627\u0637\u0629 \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062b\u0627\u0644\u062b}} ''The Poetry of Yusuf III, King of Granada''). 1958.\n* ''[[A\u1e25\u0101d\u012bth \u02bban al-adab al-Maghrib\u012b al-\u1e25ad\u012bth|A\u1e25\u0101d\u012bth \u02bban al-Adab al-Maghrib\u012b al-\u1e24ad\u012bth]]'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0623\u062d\u0627\u062f\u064a\u062b \u0639\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u062f\u064a\u062b}} ''On Modern Moroccan Literature''). 1964.\n* ''Maf\u0101h\u012bm Isl\u0101m\u012byah'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0645\u0641\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629}} ''Islamic Concepts''). 1964.\n* ''al-Muntakhab min Shi\u02bbr Ibn Z\u0101k\u016br'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u062a\u062e\u0628 \u0645\u0646 \u0634\u0639\u0631 \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0632\u0627\u0643\u0648\u0631}} ''A Selection of the Poetry of Ibn Zakur''). 1966.\n* ''Luqm\u0101n al-\u1e24ak\u012bm'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0644\u0642\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0643\u064a\u0645}} ''Luqman the Wise''). 1969.\n* ''Adab al-Fuqah\u0101\u02bc'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0642\u0647\u0627\u0621}} ''Literature of the Theologians''). 1970.\n* ''Na\u1e93rah f\u012b Munjid al-Adab wa-al-\u02bbUlum'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0646\u0638\u0631\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0645\u0646\u062c\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645}}). 1972.\n* ''al-Ta\u02bb\u0101sh\u012bb'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0634\u064a\u0628}}). 1975.\n* ''Dhikray\u0101t Mash\u0101h\u012br Rij\u0101l al-Maghrib'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0630\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0627\u062a \u0645\u0634\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0631 \u0631\u062c\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628}})''.'' 2010.\n\n==On Guennoun==\n*CHAYBI, Ahmed. ''Al-Dir\u00e2sa al `adabiyya f\u00ee al-Magrib: Al-ust\u00e2dh `Abd`all\u00e2h Kan\u0171n numudhadj'',\nT\u00e1nger: Madrasa al-Malik Fahd al-Uliy\u00e2 li-l-Tardjuma, 1991.\n*HABABI, Fatima al-Djamiya al. ''Abd all\u00e2h Kan\u0171n'', Mohammedia: Mat:ba`a Fadh\u00e2la, 1991.\nAbstract: Abdallah Guennun. Estudio biogr\u00e1fico y literario.\n*HABABI, Fatima al-Djamiya al. ''Abd all\u00e2h Kan\u0171n'', Casablanca: Mu`asasas \u0170n\u00e2, 1997.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*''Memoirs of important Men of Morocco: Ibn Battuta, Rabat:Islamic Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organisation, 1996\n*''Dhikrayat Mashahir Rijal al-Maghrib: Ahmad Zarruq, 1954\n*Mohammed Tozy, Zakya Daoud, ''Abdallah Guennoun ou le dernier des Lettr\u00e9s. LAMALIF (188), 1987:05, 13-16\n*Rom Landau, ''Portrait of Tangier'', ed. Hale, 1952, chapter 30: \"Guennoun\"\n\n==External links==\n*Afrique info (in French) [http://www.africinfo.org/index.asp?navig=personalite&no=16372&table=personnes&code=MA] (retrieved Feb. 13, 2009)\n*Tangier.free.fr (in French) [http://tangier.free.fr/Documents/Abdallah_Guennoun.htm] (retrieved Feb. 13, 2009)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guennoun, Abdallah}}\n[[Category:Moroccan writers]]\n[[Category:Moroccan essayists]]\n[[Category:Moroccan male writers]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1989 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Fez, Morocco]]\n[[Category:Moroccan historians]]\n[[Category:Moroccan academics]]\n[[Category:Moroccan scholars]]\n[[Category:20th-century historians]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n\n\n{{Morocco-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Habib Burguiba, Abdallah Guennun y Allal El Fasi presidiendo un banquete en la ciudad de T\u00e1nger en abril de 1957.jpg|thumb|261px|Guennoun (standing) during a banquet in [[Tangier]], April 1957, next to [[Habib Bourguiba]] (with [[bow tie]]) and [[Allal al-Fassi]] (with [[fez]])]]\n{{Moroccan literature}}\n'''Abdellah Guennoun''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u06ad\u0646\u0648\u0646}} \u02bbAbd All\u0101h Gann\u016bn, Born 16 September 1908 in [[Fes]] \u2013 died 9 July 1989 in [[Tangier]]) was a famous and influential Moroccan writer, historian, essayist, poet, academic, administrator, journalist, and [[Faq\u012bh|''faq\u012bh'']].<ref>Literatura Marroqui [http://www.literaturamarroqui.edu.es/autores/GHENNUN,%20Abdallah%20(1908-1989).pdf] (retrieved Feb. 13, 2009)</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hespress.com/%D9%82%D8%B1%D8%A7%D8%A1%D8%A9-%D9%81%D9%8A-%D9%83%D9%90%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%A8/160281.html|title=\"\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a\" \u0644\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u0641\u064a \u0637\u0628\u0639\u0629 \u062c\u062f\u064a\u062f\u0629|website=Hespress|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> He was one of the leaders of the ''[[Nahda]]'' movement in Morocco, and served as the general secretary of the [[League of Moroccan Religious Scholars]] ({{Lang|ar|\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0637\u0629 \u0639\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628}}).<ref>[http://www.hespress.com/?browser=view&EgyxpID=18679 '''\u0647\u064a\u0633\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0633:''' \u0630\u0627\u0643\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u062a\u0624\u0633\u0633 \u0644\u0630\u0627\u0643\u0631\u0629 \u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 \u062d\u0642\u064a\u0642\u064a\u0629] \u062a\u0627\u0631\u064a\u062e \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0635\u0648\u0644: 14 [[\u0641\u0628\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0631]] 2010]] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100216155754/http://www.hespress.com/?browser=view&EgyxpID=18679|date=16 \u0641\u0628\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0631 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hespress.com/writers/383257.html|title=\u0639\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0621 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628.. \u0645\u0646 \u0631\u0627\u0628\u0637\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0621 \u0625\u0644\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0637\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f\u064a\u0629|website=Hespress|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nHe is known for writing ''[[Al-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b|an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b]]'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a}}, ''Moroccan Intellect in Arabic Literature''),<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Simour|first=Lhoussain|url=https://books.google.co.ma/books?id=FABODQAAQBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=guennoun+literature&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiG_6Xdo8DoAhUj2uAKHUKPDZ0Q6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=guennoun%20literature&f=false|title=Larbi Batma, Nass el-Ghiwane and Postcolonial Music in Morocco|date=2016-10-21|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-1-4766-2581-2|language=en}}</ref> a three-volume anthology of [[Moroccan literature]] in [[Arabic]] that was banned by the [[French Protectorate in Morocco|French Protectorate]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.habous.gov.ma/daouat-alhaq/item/1234|title=\u062f\u0639\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0642 - [\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0628] \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a (\u0644\u0640 \u0639.\u0644.\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646)|website=www.habous.gov.ma|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.maghress.com/almassae/211388|title=\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0644\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646.. \u0645\u0648\u0633\u0648\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0641\u064a \u062e\u0635\u0648\u0635\u064a\u062a\u0647 \u0648\u062a\u0639\u062f\u062f\u0647|website=\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0633|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> \n\nGuennoun also served as a member of a number of linguistic, educational, and Islamic academies and organizations in places such as [[Rabat]], [[Cairo]], [[Damascus]], [[Baghdad]], and [[Amman]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://uemnet.free.fr/guide/kaf/kaf07.htm|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0640\u0648\u0646|website=uemnet.free.fr|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nAbdallah Guennoun was born in Fes in 1908 to a family of noble [[Idrisid dynasty|Idrissid]] lineage long associated with knowledge.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref> His family moved from Fes to Tangier in 1914.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nHe had a traditional Islamic education, memorizing the [[Quran]] and some [[Hadith]].<ref name=\":4\" /> With access to international books in Tangier, he also taught himself [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and [[French language|French]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nGuennoun began his writing career early; he published in the newspaper [[Idhar al-Haqq|''Idhar al-Haqq'']] ({{Lang|ar|\u0625\u0638\u0647\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0642}}) in 1927 when he was 20 years old.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EGtlrenmK0A|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646 1 - \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628|date=Aug 24, 2016|work=\u0627\u0644\u062c\u0632\u064a\u0631\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0648\u062b\u0627\u0626\u0642\u064a\u0629|access-date=|url-status=live|language=Arabic}}</ref> He also wrote for publications such as the Egyptian literary magazine ''[[Arrissalah]].<ref name=\":4\" />''\n\nHe became active and influential in the flourishing intellectual and cultural scene in [[T\u00e9touan|Tetuan]], and he published many of his works there.<ref name=\":2\" /> As part of this intellectual circle in Tetuan, he was involved in the first nationalist publication in Morocco, ''[[As-Salaam (publication)|as-Salaam]]'', which published its first issue October 1933.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.habous.gov.ma/daouat-alhaq/item/5281|title=\u062f\u0639\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0642 - \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0623\u0648\u0644 \u0635\u062d\u064a\u0641\u0629 \u0648\u0637\u0646\u064a\u0629 \u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629|website=www.habous.gov.ma|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAbdallah Guennoun was well-connected, associated with [[Said Hajji]] in the [[French Protectorate in Morocco|French area]], [[Mohammed Daoud]] in the [[Spanish protectorate in Morocco|Spanish area]], and [[Shakib Arslan]] in the ''[[Mashriq]]''.<ref name=\":2\" /> Guennoun became involved with the [[Moroccan Action Committee]] in 1934.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\nHe opened the first of the [[Moroccan free schools]] in Tangier, the Free Abdallah Guennoun School ({{Lang|ar|\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u0629 \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0629}}), and worked as a teacher in 1936.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nHe was the editor in-chief of a monthly Islamic publication called [[Lisaan ad-Din (publication)|''Lisaan ad-Din'']] ({{Lang|ar|\u0644\u0633\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646}}) in the 1940s and published a number of articles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> He also served as the general secretary of [[Al-Mithaq (newspaper)|''al-Mithaq'']], a journal put out by the faculty of [[University of al-Qarawiyyin|al-Qarawiyyin University]].<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.habous.gov.ma/daouat-alhaq/item/5427|title=\u062f\u0639\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0642 - \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646 \u0648\u0623\u062b\u0631\u0647 \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062b\u0642\u0627\u0641\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629 -2-|website=www.habous.gov.ma|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\nHe refused the support [[Mohammed Ben Aarafa]], the [[puppet monarch]] chosen by France to replace [[Mohammed V of Morocco|Muhammad V]], whom France had exiled.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nGuennoun was, among other members of the [[Mococcan Nationalist Movement]] ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0631\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0648\u0637\u0646\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a\u0629}}) including [[Allal al-Fassi]], [[Abdelkhalek Torres]], [[Abdallah Ibrahim]], a member of a generation of Moroccan intellectuals brought together the political and the cultural, and who criticized the reform movement in the country, arguing that there can be \"no reform without independence.\"<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\n=== ''an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b'' ===\nIn 1938, he published ''[[Al-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b|an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b]]'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a}}, ''Moroccan Intellect in Arabic Literature''), his three-volume anthology of [[Moroccan literature]].<ref name=\":0\" /> This anthology indexed and contextualized major Moroccan works of literature written in [[Arabic]], and led to the development of a Moroccan literary canon.<ref name=\":3\" /> Affirming both Morocco's contributions to [[Arabic literature]] and the long tradition of Arabic literature in Morocco, ''an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b'' was seen as a nationalist reaction to colonialism.<ref name=\":3\" /> It was banned by the authorities of the [[French Protectorate in Morocco|French Protectorate]], and could not be brought into the area under French colonial control, nor could it be sold, displayed, or distributed there.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Spain, however, was receptive of the work; ''an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b'' was translated into Spanish and Abdallah Guennoun was granted an honorary doctorate from a university in Madrid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.belpresse.com/featured/105958.html|title=\u0627\u0644\u0630\u0643\u0631\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0626\u0648\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0645\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062f \u0635\u0627\u062d\u0628 '\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a'|date=2019-09-20|website=Belpresse {{!}} \u0628\u0644\u0628\u0631\u064a\u0633|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> \n\nHe held a number of different positions. In 1937, he was made director of the [[Khalifi Institute]] ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u0647\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062e\u0644\u064a\u0641\u064a}}),<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://uemnet.free.fr/guide/kaf/kaf07.htm|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0640\u0648\u0646|website=uemnet.free.fr|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://marayana.com/laune/2019/09/17/2457/|title=\u0641\u064a \u0630\u0643\u0631\u0649 \u0645\u064a\u0644\u0627\u062f\u0647: \u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646\u2026 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0630\u064a \u0623\u0639\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0639\u062a\u0628\u0627\u0631 \u0644\u0644\u0641\u0643\u0631 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a|last=\u0627\u0644\u0647\u0627\u0646\u064a|first=\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0645|date=2019-09-17|website=Marayana - \u0645\u0631\u0627\u064a\u0627\u0646\u0627|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> then professor at the [[High Institute of Religion]] ({{Lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0639\u0647\u062f \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u064a}}) and the [[College of Theology in Tetuan]] ({{Lang|ar|\u0643\u0644\u064a\u0629 \u0623\u0635\u0648\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u062f\u064a\u0646 \u0628\u062a\u0637\u0648\u0627\u0646}}).<ref name=\":8\" /> He held the office of Minister of Justice in the Khalifi government from 1954 to 1956.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nHe became a member of the [[Arab Academy of Damascus]] in 1956, the [[Academy of the Arabic Language in Cairo]] in 1961, the [[League of Moroccan Religious Scholars]], the [[al-Quds Scientific Commision]] ({{Lang|ar|\u0647\u064a\u0626\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u0633 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0629}}) in 1973, the [[Muslim World League]] in Mecca as a founding member in 1974, the [[Jordan Academy of Arabic]] in 1978, the [[Iraqi Academy of Sciences]] in 1979, and the [[Academy of the Kingdom of Morocco]] in 1980.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nIn 1981, he founded ''[[al-Ihyaa']]'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0625\u062d\u064a\u0627\u0621}} ''The Revival''), a journal published by the Association of Moroccan Academics focusing on Islamic theological sciences and thought from an open, critical perspective.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arrabita.ma/blog/%d9%86%d8%a8%d8%b0%d8%a9-%d8%aa%d8%b9%d8%b1%d9%8a%d9%81%d9%8a%d8%a9-%d8%b9%d9%86-%d9%85%d8%ac%d9%84%d8%a9-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%a5%d8%ad%d9%8a%d8%a7%d8%a1/|title=\u0646\u0628\u0630\u0629 \u062a\u0639\u0631\u064a\u0641\u064a\u0629 \u0639\u0646 \u0645\u062c\u0644\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u062d\u064a\u0627\u0621|date=2019-06-19|website=\u0628\u0648\u0627\u0628\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0627\u0628\u0637\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0621|language=ar|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nAbdallah Guennoun passed away July 9, 1989 in Tangier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.net/encyclopedia/icons/2014/11/14/\u0639\u0628\u062f-\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647-\u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|title=\u0639\u0628\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0643\u0646\u0648\u0646|website=www.aljazeera.net|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Notable works ==\nAbdallah Guennoun's works include poetry, literary fiction, and history. Some of his most notable works include:\n\n* ''[[Al-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b|an-Nub\u016bgh al-Maghrib\u012b f\u012b al-adab al-\u02bbArab\u012b]]'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0646\u0628\u0648\u063a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0641\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0631\u0628\u064a}}, ''Moroccan Intellect in Arabic Literature''), 1st ed. [[al-Matba'a al-Mehdia]]. 1938; 2nd ed. [[Dar al-Kitab al-Lubnani]]. 1961; 1st ed. [[Dar al-Kutub al-Ilmiyah]]. 2014.\n* ''Umar\u0101\u02bcun\u0101 al-Shu\u02bbar\u0101\u02bc'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0623\u0645\u0631\u0627\u0624\u0646\u0627 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0631\u0627\u0621}} ''Our Poet Princes''). 1941.\n* ''al-Qudwat ul-Samiya lil-Nashi'at il-Islamiya'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u0648\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629 \u0644\u0644\u0646\u0627\u0634\u0626\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629}}). 1945\n* ''Wahat al-Fikr'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0648\u0627\u062d\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0643\u0631}} ''The Oasis of Thought'')''.'' 1948.\n* ''D\u012bw\u0101n Malik Gharna\u1e6dah Yusuf al-Thalith'' ({{Lang|ar|\u062f\u064a\u0648\u0627\u0646 \u0645\u0627\u0644\u0643 \u063a\u0631\u0646\u0627\u0637\u0629 \u064a\u0648\u0633\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u062b\u0627\u0644\u062b}} ''The Poetry of Yusuf III, King of Granada''). 1958.\n* ''[[A\u1e25\u0101d\u012bth \u02bban al-adab al-Maghrib\u012b al-\u1e25ad\u012bth|A\u1e25\u0101d\u012bth \u02bban al-Adab al-Maghrib\u012b al-\u1e24ad\u012bth]]'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0623\u062d\u0627\u062f\u064a\u062b \u0639\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u062f\u064a\u062b}} ''On Modern Moroccan Literature''). 1964.\n* ''Maf\u0101h\u012bm Isl\u0101m\u012byah'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0645\u0641\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0645 \u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a\u0629}} ''Islamic Concepts''). 1964.\n* ''al-Muntakhab min Shi\u02bbr Ibn Z\u0101k\u016br'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0646\u062a\u062e\u0628 \u0645\u0646 \u0634\u0639\u0631 \u0627\u0628\u0646 \u0632\u0627\u0643\u0648\u0631}} ''A Selection of the Poetry of Ibn Zakur''). 1966.\n* ''Luqm\u0101n al-\u1e24ak\u012bm'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0644\u0642\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0643\u064a\u0645}} ''Luqman the Wise''). 1969.\n* ''Adab al-Fuqah\u0101\u02bc'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0642\u0647\u0627\u0621}} ''Literature of the Theologians''). 1970.\n* ''Na\u1e93rah f\u012b Munjid al-Adab wa-al-\u02bbUlum'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0646\u0638\u0631\u0629 \u0641\u064a \u0645\u0646\u062c\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0623\u062f\u0628 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0644\u0648\u0645}}). 1972.\n* ''al-Ta\u02bb\u0101sh\u012bb'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0627\u0644\u062a\u0639\u0627\u0634\u064a\u0628}}). 1975.\n* ''Dhikray\u0101t Mash\u0101h\u012br Rij\u0101l al-Maghrib'' ({{Lang|ar|\u0630\u0643\u0631\u064a\u0627\u062a \u0645\u0634\u0627\u0647\u064a\u0631 \u0631\u062c\u0627\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u063a\u0631\u0628}})''.'' 2010.\n\n==On Guennoun==\n*CHAYBI, Ahmed. ''Al-Dir\u00e2sa al `adabiyya f\u00ee al-Magrib: Al-ust\u00e2dh `Abd`all\u00e2h Kan\u0171n numudhadj'',\nT\u00e1nger: Madrasa al-Malik Fahd al-Uliy\u00e2 li-l-Tardjuma, 1991.\n*HABABI, Fatima al-Djamiya al. ''Abd all\u00e2h Kan\u0171n'', Mohammedia: Mat:ba`a Fadh\u00e2la, 1991.\nAbstract: Abdallah Guennun. Estudio biogr\u00e1fico y literario.\n*HABABI, Fatima al-Djamiya al. ''Abd all\u00e2h Kan\u0171n'', Casablanca: Mu`asasas \u0170n\u00e2, 1997.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*''Memoirs of important Men of Morocco: Ibn Battuta, Rabat:Islamic Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organisation, 1996\n*''Dhikrayat Mashahir Rijal al-Maghrib: Ahmad Zarruq, 1954\n*Mohammed Tozy, Zakya Daoud, ''Abdallah Guennoun ou le dernier des Lettr\u00e9s. LAMALIF (188), 1987:05, 13-16\n*Rom Landau, ''Portrait of Tangier'', ed. Hale, 1952, chapter 30: \"Guennoun\"\n\n==External links==\n*Afrique info (in French) [http://www.africinfo.org/index.asp?navig=personalite&no=16372&table=personnes&code=MA] (retrieved Feb. 13, 2009)\n*Tangier.free.fr (in French) [http://tangier.free.fr/Documents/Abdallah_Guennoun.htm] (retrieved Feb. 13, 2009)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guennoun, Abdallah}}\n[[Category:Moroccan writers]]\n[[Category:Moroccan essayists]]\n[[Category:Moroccan male writers]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1989 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Fez, Morocco]]\n[[Category:Moroccan historians]]\n[[Category:Moroccan academics]]\n[[Category:Moroccan scholars]]\n[[Category:20th-century historians]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n\n\n{{Morocco-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nick Number", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp commissionWP:TYPO", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abdellah_Guennoun"}
